#Text=William
#Text=Forrest ( poet )
#Text=William Forrest ( fl. 1581 ) was an English Catholic priest and poet .
#Text=Life
#Text=Forrest is stated by Anthony Wood to have been a relative of John Forest , the Franciscan friar .

#Text=He received his education at Christ Church , Oxford , and he was present at the discussions held at Oxford in 1530 , when Henry VIII desired to procure the judgment of the university in the matter of his divorce ; he appears to have attended the funeral of Queen Catherine of Aragon at Peterborough in 1536 .
#Text=He was an eyewitness of the erection of Wolsey 's Cardinal College on the site of the priory of St. Frideswide , and he was appointed to a post in the college as refounded by the king .
#Text=In 1553 he came forward with congratulations on the accession of Queen Mary , and was soon afterwards nominated one of the queen 's chaplains . [ 1 ]
#Text=Of his career after the death of Mary nothing certain is known .
#Text=He was probably protected by Thomas Howard , 2nd Duke of Norfolk , to whom he dedicated his ‘ History of Joseph ’ shortly before the duke 's execution in 1572 .
#Text=Forrest remained a Catholic .
#Text=This is shown by the fact that the two dates ‘ 27 Oct. 1572 , per me Guil .
#Text=Forrestum , ’ and ‘ 1581 ’ occur in a volume ( Harl . MS . 1703 ) containing a poem which in a devout tone treats of the life of the Blessed Virgin and of the Immaculate Conception .
#Text=But he was not papalist , and in one of his poems he speaks strongly of the right of each national branch of the church to enjoy self-government .
#Text=He was well skilled in music , and had a collection of the compositions then in vogue .
#Text=These manuscripts came into the hands of William Heather , founder of the musical praxis and professorship at Oxford , and are preserved in the archives there .
#Text=Forrest was on terms of friendship with Alexander Barclay .
#Text=There is a portrait of him in the Royal MS . 17 D. iii .
#Text=He is represented as a young man in a priest 's gown , and with long flowing hair not tonsured .
#Text=Works
#Text=In 1548 he dedicated his version of the treatise De regimine Principum to the Duke of Somerset , and also in 1551 his paraphrase of some of the Psalms .
#Text=In 1558 Forrest presented to Queen Mary his poem of ‘ The Second Gresyld . ’
#Text=His poetical works are :
#Text=‘ The History of Joseph the Chaiste composed in balladde royall crudely ; largely derived from the Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs .

#Text=In two parts . ’ Dedicated to Thomas Howard , duke of Norfolk , and dated as having been finished 11 April 1569 , but said by the author to have been originally written twenty-four years before .
#Text=The first part , written on vellum , is in the library of University College , Oxford , and the second part is in the Royal manuscripts , British Library , 18 C. xiii .
#Text=A copy of both parts in one folio volume of 286 pages , written on paper , was collected by Sir Thomas Phillipps .

#Text=‘ A Notable Warke called the pleasant Poesie of princelie Practise , composed of late by the simple and unlearned Sir William Forrest , priest , much part collected out of a booke entitled the “ Governance of Noblemen , ” which booke the wyse philosopher Aristotle wrote to his disciple Alexander the Great . ’
#Text=This work , written in 1548 , and dedicated to the Duke of Somerset , was intended for the use of Edward VI .
#Text=A long extract from it is printed in ‘ England in the Reign of Henry VIII .
#Text=Starkey 's Life and Letters ’ ( Early English Text Society ) , 1878 , pt . i. p. lxxix seq .
#Text=The treatise referred to in the title , ‘ De regimine Principum , ’ was written by Ægidius Romanus .
#Text=A metrical version of some of the Psalms , written in 1551 , and also dedicated to the Duke of Somerset .
#Text=‘ A New Ballade of the Marigolde .
#Text=Imprinted at London in Aldersgate Street by Richard Lant ’ [ 1553 ] .
#Text=Verses on the accession of Queen Mary .
#Text=The ballad was reprinted by Thomas Park in the second edition of the ‘ Harleian Miscellany ’ ( 1813 ) .
#Text=Pater Noster and Te Deum , versified as a prayer and a thanksgiving for Queen Mary .
#Text=In the first edition of John Foxe 's Actes and Monuments ( 1563 ) .

#Text=‘ A true and most notable History of a right noble and famous Lady , produced in Spain , entitled The Second Gresyld , practised not long out of this time , in much part Tragedious , as delectable both to Hearers and Readers , ’ folio .
#Text=In the manuscripts of Anthony Wood in the Bodleian Library ; it was given to Wood by Ralph Sheldon of Weston Park , Warwickshire .
#Text=The work , which was finished 25 June 1558 , is a narrative in verse of the divorce of Queen Catherine of Aragon .
#Text=Wood extracted some passages for his English ‘ Annals of the University of Oxford . ’
#Text=These are printed in John Gutch 's edition of the ‘ Annals ’ ( 1796 ) , ii . 47 , 115 .
#Text=The ninth chapter was contributed by Philip Bliss in 1814 to Sir Samuel Egerton Brydges 's ‘ British Bibliographer , ’ iv . 200 .
#Text=The entire poem was printed by the Roxburghe Club , with the title of ‘ The History of Grisild the Second , ’ London , 1875 , edited by William Dunn Macray .
#Text=‘ An Oration consolatorye to Queen Marye . ’
#Text=At the end of the preceding work .
#Text=Life of the Blessed Virgin Mary , being a poem in praise of her and in honour of the Immaculate Conception , followed by miscellaneous , moral , and religious verses , dated from 1572 to 1581 .
